If no new InstallPlan was created after removing startingCSV, then OLM still considers the subscription resolved to the currently installed CSV.

Most likely reason:

The package channel graph itself still resolves stable-4.19 → 4.18.17-rhodf for that specific subscription chain.

Let's verify exactly what OLM sees.

Run this:

oc get packagemanifest rook-ceph-operator -o yaml

Check carefully under:

status:
  channels:

You will probably see something like:

- currentCSV: rook-ceph-operator.v4.18.17-rhodf
  name: stable-4.18

- currentCSV: rook-ceph-operator.v4.19.12-rhodf
  name: stable-4.19

Now compare with the subscription:

oc get sub -n openshift-storage rook-ceph-operator-stable-4.18-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace -o yaml | grep channel

If it already says:

channel: stable-4.19

then force reconciliation once:

oc delete pod -n openshift-marketplace --all
oc delete pod -n openshift-operator-lifecycle-manager --all

Wait 2–5 minutes.

Then check:

oc get installplan -A
oc get csv -A

If still no new installplan, then the subscription may need recreation because it was originally generated by odf-operator.

Important clue from your YAML:

olm.managed: "true"
ownerReferences:
- kind: Subscription
  name: odf-operator

That means the umbrella odf-operator is managing these child subscriptions and may be reconciling them back.

In that case, the correct approach is NOT manually editing child subscriptions.

Instead verify whether the StorageCluster/ODF CR has upgrade controls.

Check:

oc get storagecluster ocs-storagecluster -n openshift-storage -o yaml

Look for:

spec.version

spec.channel

spec.allowUnsupported

upgrade-related fields


Most likely the ODF operator intentionally keeps those supporting operators on 4.18.17 while only the umbrella operator is 4.19.12.
